Error handling — try, catch, and finally.

Scala has the java-style try, catch, and finally, and the nice difference is that the bodies are expressions. So you can bind the result of a try to a val. The shape is a try around a risky operation, a catch with a case clause for the relevant exception that returns a fallback value, and an optional finally that always runs a cleanup step, whether or not anything threw.

The right place for try-catch is at the edge of your program — a main method, or a hypertext-transfer-protocol request handler — where you need to translate an exception into a response or an exit code. Picture a parse-quantity that tries to convert a string, catches a number-format exception by printing a message and returning zero, and runs a cleanup line in finally either way. On valid input it returns the number and still runs the cleanup; on bad input it reports the error, returns zero, and still runs the cleanup.

But inside your logic, the try, option, and either types from notebook six are usually cleaner. They make failure part of the type rather than an out-of-band channel that travels invisibly up the call stack. So use try-catch-finally at the boundary, where you must deal with the java exception model directly, and prefer the typed failure types everywhere in between, where you want failure to be a value you can see and compose.
